 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/umananin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mananin</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=  http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif  BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CoG Companion</span><br>  Posts: 61<br> <font color=#8E9173>(6/28/01 6:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=211.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Guess on Dragon Raids</span><hr size=1> I think the guest rules for KCoG are fine.  I think allowing anyone under 53 for dragon raids is the right idea.  It's more important to KILL THAT DARN LIZARD (no offense my scaley iksar friends), than it is to exclude uber-guilded or alliance folk from the raid so that non-ubers get a better chance at lewtz.  Was I disappointed that Ogun won the eyepatch instead of a scrub like me? Yeah, a little.  Heck, I was a little disappointed that a guy in Silver Daggers won a Cloak of Flames.  But then I remembered that that bard was feeding me and three others mana in the buff line, and he certainly wasn't just sitting around when we were fighting Big Red.  And Ogun rezzed at least 6 friends of mine, and there weren't any other 56+ clerics there, so those rezzes were invaluable.  The question you have to ask yourself is, would we have won without them?  I don't know.  You don't know.  And it's that uncertainty that gives them the right to join us and to roll for loot.<br>
Look at it this way, there is now one more eyepatch and one more cloak on the server.  The more stuff there is out there, the better chance that someone will sell it to you for a cheap price.  I couldn't have afforded my Dark Ember if there were'nt so many of them around.  Heck, a complete stranger gave me my Jaundiced Helm that i was using to buff people with (never underestimate the power of charisma <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) The economy of EQ is one of deflation, and when you are a scrub like me, that works to your advantage.<br>
Now plane raids are a different story, and KCoG has rules and guidelines specific for those, however, these really aren't written in stone.  Every raid is unique, and the situation can call for a either strict adherance to the rules or bending of them.  If I were running a plane raid, and we had enough people to make it a success, then I would turn away someone from Valoran, even Lagdalen, unless they said they wouldn't roll for anything, in which case, I'd agree to let them join if their added presence wouldn't cause the zone to lag.  If there was nobody of a certain class on the raid, than I would let an uber-guilded person of that class come along, to loot only no-drop class specific stuff.  Heck, why not? <br>
If we were short on people enough to jeopardize the success of the raid, than I would invite pretty much anyone I could get.<br>
So what if Valoran puts restrictions on guest-looting rules?  Hey, if you want to join them on a raid, you should know in advance what they are gonna let you loot.  Then you make the decision whether you want to join them or not.  The odds are they don't need you, and it's not like they announce publicly they are raiding ToV and inviting anyone who wants to come along. <br>
Yeah, there are some people I don't like in Valoran. But there are people I don't like in other guilds too.  No guild is perfect.  And I do like quite a few people in Valoran anyway.  I haven't gotten the impression that any one guild is trying to own the server.  I like the way Karana is set up so that things are shared and everyone pretty much gets along.   I think an anarchist would be pretty disappointed to play on our server, hehe. GOOD!<br>
<br>
Vudu Majek<br>
52 Mystic<br>
Emerald Axe<br>
